Bergmanns rule predicts that organisms at higher latitudes are larger than ones at lower latitudes. Bergmanns Rule can be observed in fiddler crab carapace width data collected along the United States Atlantic coast (Johnson 2019). The below figure shows a general trend of increases carapace widths with increasing latitudes.

The below table shows a summary of the data collected at each site (by ID), including the total sample size for each site.

Mean carapace width in mm, standard deviation (mm), and crab sample size at each site to test Bergmanns Rule.

Generally speaking, higher latitude waters tend to have colder mean temperatures. This contiues to show the correlation between latitude and carapace width. The box plot is included to show that there is still variation within this correlation, expecially the 14.01 Celcius site.

Citation: Johnson, D. 2019. Fiddler crab body size in salt marshes from Florida to Massachusetts, USA at PIE and VCR LTER and NOAA NERR sites during summer 2016. ver 1. Environmental Data Initiative. https://doi.org/10.6073/pasta/4c27d2e778d3325d3830a5142e3839bb (Accessed 2021-08-20).
